ing, XML configuration for optional package mappings, dispatch target class table, and a note about \".\" to \"/\" replacement for backward compatibility.\n\nLet me examine the XML structure for the complex mapping more carefully...\n\nLooking at the XML, I see there's a mismatch between what the source text describes and what's actually in the configuration. The source text mentions request patterns like `/sample/admin//` and `/sample/user//`, but the XML shows just `/admin//` and `/user//` without the `/sample/` prefix. The knowledge file matches the XML exactly, so there's a discrepancy between the documentation and the actual implementation that I need to account for.\n\nNow checking the dispatch target mappings, both the source and knowledge file show the same routing: `/admin/AdminApp` goes to `nablarch.sample.apps1.admin.AdminApp`, `/user/UserApp` goes to `nablarch.sample.apps2.user.UserApp`, and `/BaseApp` routes to the base package. These align correctly.\n\nFor the section count, I'm recounting the RST headings more carefully—the main title is h1, then there are three h2 sections for the overview, handler flow, and configuration items. The knowledge file has three sections that should correspond to these, though the pre-check warning flagged a mismatch that I need to verify by looking at the actual structure. I need to recount the heading levels more carefully by looking at the RST underline characters. The `+` character is indeed valid for headings in RST, so I should trace through the document structure systematically to see where all six headings actually appear and what level each one represents. I'm realizing these `+++` sequences aren't actually RST headings—they're just visual separators without preceding text. In RST, a heading requires text followed by an underline, so these standalone delimiter lines don't create heading levels. The actual structure appears to be H1 and H2 sections with these `+++` lines functioning as dividers within the content